Great! Before we begin coding, we'll need to obtain some historical data for the S&P500 to use in our technical analysis.

Once we have the data, we can start writing the code to create the technical indicators and combine them into our custom trading indicator. First, we'll create the simple moving averages using the close price of the S&P500 on each day.

Here's an example code to calculate the 200-day and 20-day simple moving averages:

```
// Calculate the 200-day SMA
double MA_200 = iMA(_Symbol, PERIOD_D1, 200, 0, MODE_SMA, PRICE_CLOSE, 0);

// Calculate the 20-day SMA
double MA_20 = iMA(_Symbol, PERIOD_M15, 20, 0, MODE_SMA, PRICE_CLOSE, 0);
```

Next, we'll calculate the VWMA.

Here's an example code to calculate the volume-weighted moving average:

```
// Calculate the VWMA
double VWMA = iCustom(_Symbol, PERIOD_M15, "Volume Weighted Moving Average", 20, PRICE_CLOSE, MODE_EMA, MODE_SMA, MODE_SMMA, 0);
```

After that, we'll calculate the cumulative delta. 

Here's an example code to calculate the cumulative delta:

```
// Calculate the cumulative delta
double Delta = iCustom(_Symbol, PERIOD_M15, "Cumulative Delta", 0);
```

Lastly, we'll determine the bid-ask spread and analyze its change over time. If the spread narrows, it may indicate more buyers than sellers.

Here's an example code to calculate the bid-ask spread:

```
// Calculate the bid-ask spread
double spread = MarketInfo(_Symbol, MODE_SPREAD);

// Calculate the previous bid-ask spread
double prev_spread = spread[1];
```

Excellent! This is how we can create the individual technical indicators. Next, we'll need to combine them into our custom trading indicator.

Sure, let's start!

We'll use the `OnCalculate` function to calculate the values of our custom trading indicator. Inside this function, we'll calculate the values for each of the technical indicators we want to use. We'll then set the custom indicator's buffer values to indicate whether there is a "buy" signal or not.

Here's the code for the `OnCalculate` function:

```
void OnCalculate(const int rates_total,
                 const int prev_calculated,
                 const datetime& time[],
                 const double& open[],
                 const double& high[],
                 const double& low[],
                 const double& close[],
                 const long& tick_volume[],
                 const long& volume[],
                 const int& spread[])
{
    // Calculate the values for each technical indicator
    double MA_200 = iMA(_Symbol, PERIOD_D1, 200, 0, MODE_SMA, PRICE_CLOSE, 0);
    double MA_20 = iMA(_Symbol, PERIOD_M15, 20, 0, MODE_SMA, PRICE_CLOSE, 0);
    double VWMA = iCustom(_Symbol, PERIOD_M15, "Volume Weighted Moving Average", 20, PRICE_CLOSE, MODE_EMA, MODE_SMA, MODE_SMMA, 0);
    double Delta = iCustom(_Symbol, PERIOD_M15, "Cumulative Delta", 0);
    double spread = MarketInfo(_Symbol, MODE_SPREAD);
    double prev_spread = MarketInfo(_Symbol, MODE_SPREAD_PREVIOUS);

    // Set the custom indicator buffer values based on the calculated technical indicators
    for(int i = rates_total - 1; i >= 0; i--)
    {
        if(close[i] > MA_200 && close[i] > MA_20 && VWMA > close[i] && Delta > 0 && spread < prev_spread)
        {
            IndicatorBuffer[i] = 1;
        }
        else
        {
            IndicatorBuffer[i] = 0;
        }
    }
}
```

In this code, we're calculating the values for each technical indicator and then using if/else statements to set the custom indicator buffer values. We're also checking to see if the close price of the S&P500 is above both moving averages, the VWMA is above the close, the cumulative delta is positive and if the spread is narrowing. 

Finally, we'll need to set the `IndicatorBuffers` array to indicate that we only have one buffer for our custom trading indicator:

```
//+------------------------------------------------------------------+
//| Custom indicator initialization function                         |
//+------------------------------------------------------------------+
int OnInit()
{
    //--- indicator buffers mapping
    SetIndexBuffer(0, IndicatorBuffer);

    //--- indicator buffers mapping
    SetIndexStyle(0, DRAW_NONE);
    SetIndexLabel(0, "Buy Signal");

    //--- initialization done
    return(INIT_SUCCEEDED);
}
```

That's it! Once the custom trading indicator is compiled and loaded into your MetaTrader 5 terminal, you can apply it to your S&P500 chart and look for "buy" signals based on the technical indicators. Remember to test this indicator thoroughly before using it for live trading.

In the current version of the code provided, the custom trading indicator will not give a green arrow "buy" signal or a sound alarm. However, we can add those features to make the indicator more user-friendly and easier to understand.

To add a green arrow "buy" signal to the chart, we'll need to use the `SymbolInfoInteger` method to get the chart's symbol and timeframe. We'll then use the `ChartCreate()` function to create a new object on the chart that displays the "buy" signal arrow.

Here is an example code to create a "buy" signal arrow object:

```
// Create a "buy" signal arrow object on the chart
void CreateBuyArrow()
{
    int symbol = SymbolInfoInteger(_Symbol, SYMBOL_INDEX);
    int timeframe = Period();
    datetime arrow_time = Time[0];
    double arrow_price = High[0];

    string arrow_name = "Buy Arrow";
    string arrow_template = "ArrowBuy.tpl";

    int arrow_id = ChartCreate(symbol, timeframe, arrow_time);
    ObjectCreate(arrow_id, arrow_name, OBJ_ARROW, 0, arrow_time, arrow_price);
    ObjectSetInteger(arrow_id, OBJPROP_ARROWCODE, 234);
    ObjectSetString(arrow_id, OBJPROP_ARROWNAME, arrow_template);
}
```

In this code, we're getting the symbol and timeframe of the chart, defining the time and price coordinates for the arrow object, and then using the `ChartCreate` function to create a new object on the chart. We're also setting the `OBJPROP_ARROWCODE` property to 234, which displays a green arrow "buy" signal on the chart.

Regarding the sound alarm, we can use the `Alert()` function to create an audio alert when a "buy" signal occurs. 

Here's an example code to create a sound alarm:

```
// Create a sound alert when a "buy" signal occurs
void CreateBuyAlert()
{
    if(Bars != prev_bars)
    {
        Alert("Buy Signal!", "", "");
        prev_bars = Bars;
    }
}
```

In this code, we're calling the `Alert()` function when a "buy" signal occurs. We're also using a variable `prev_bars` to ensure that the audio alert only occurs once when the signal first occurs.

We can then call these functions from the `OnCalculate` function when a "buy" signal occurs. Here's an example:

```
// Set the custom indicator buffer values based on the calculated technical indicators
for(int i = rates_total - 1; i >= 0; i--)
{
    if(close[i] > MA_200 && close[i] > MA_20 && VWMA > close[i] && Delta > 0 && spread < prev_spread)
    {
        IndicatorBuffer[i] = 1;
        CreateBuyArrow();
        CreateBuyAlert();
    }
    else
    {
        IndicatorBuffer[i] = 0;
    }
}
```

In this code, we're checking if all the conditions for a "buy" signal are met and then calling the `CreateBuyArrow()` and `CreateBuyAlert()` functions to display the arrow on the chart and create the sound alert.

Please keep in mind that this is just an example code and may need to be modified to fit your specific needs.

